  "topic_name": "Pressure",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Pressure is defined as force per unit area. When the same force is applied over a smaller area, pressure increases. The SI unit of pressure is Pascal (Pa). Pressure in liquids increases with depth and acts equally in all directions at a point. Atmospheric pressure is the pressure exerted by air on all surfaces. Evidence of atmospheric pressure includes phenomena like drinking through a straw and suction cups sticking to surfaces. Pressure concepts explain many everyday observations like why sharp knives cut better and why buildings need broad foundations.",
    "rules": [
      "Pressure = Force / Area.",
      "SI unit of pressure: Pascal (Pa) = N/m^2.",
      "Same force on smaller area = greater pressure.",
      "Pressure in liquids increases with depth.",
      "Liquids exert pressure in all directions.",
      "Atmospheric pressure: pressure exerted by air.",
      "Drinking straws work due to atmospheric pressure."
    ]
  },
